node.text:
For the past few months, I have been working on creating an online offering that has the same feel and quality content of an in-person event. Together with Soren of @wisdom2events and @guynamedlindsey we have created Committed to the Journey. It is an interview series where I cover topics from relationships, unlocking creativity, healing and growth, my personal story, how inner-work impacts society, and much more. I try to keep my events accessible and this will be no different, for $20 you can access all of the interviews, which is more than 3 hours of content. You can access the videos by going to the top link in my bio or by going directly to vimeo.com/ondemand/committedtothejourney or by checking out my stories. Really excited to bring you this series; in a way this feels like the direct follow up to my first book Inward. I hope it serves you well.

Sending love to all 🙏🏽 #yungpueblo

Hey friends, a segment aired on @nightline on @abcnetwork last night featuring my work as a writer and speaker. It is surreal seeing this summary of things. I didn’t know how everything would turn out when I started sharing my writing on Instagram back in 2015. Grateful to everyone who helped along the way. Special thanks to @lauraecoburn for producing this piece and @danharris and the @tenpercenthappier team for interviewing me. Also @sacredspacemiami for letting us get footage of the event. Sending much love to all beings. #yungpueblo

node.text:
It is not easy, but it is worth the effort.

What technique or practice has helped you let go? There is a lot out there, so it is helpful to hear what is actually helping people move forward.

Different practices work for different people because we all have unique conditioning. Personally, meditating Vipassana in the U Ba Khin/S.N. Goenka tradition has helped me deeply.

Sending love to all beings. May we all be happy and free. 🙏🏽🌎 #yungpueblo

node.text:
When we are in the habit of ignoring what we feel or consistently run away from hard parts of ourselves, distance is created not just between us and ourselves but also between us and other people. Our lack of a full embrace of all that we are can make our interactions with others superficial, even if there is a desire to connect deeply with someone, that connection will encounter limits and will only ever reach a depth equal to the relationship we have with ourselves. Our personal degree of self-awareness will reflect dimly or brightly on whomever crosses our path.
 
If we can observe our emotions with open arms full of compassion, it will be much easier to show up and support others when they are going through a moment of personal turbulence. If we can embrace our own complexity, we will have patience as we learn more about those closest to us. If we have experience facing our own hard truths and being present through our personal ups and downs, we will have the emotional fortitude to wisely handle challenging moments in a relationship without immediately running away.
 
There is no other way to a life of fulfillment, happiness and vibrant connections, but through thoroughly traveling the realms of our own heart and mind. Areas that remain undiscovered are areas of potential friction that may manifest in our own mind or between us and the ones we love. All that is unexplored can show up as blocks that can stop the flow of harmony.
 
If we are accustomed to brave observation and practicing acceptance when inner turbulence tries to bring our attention to an unexplored or unloved part of ourselves, then the moments of friction within us or in our relationships will not become blocks. Instead, these tough moments will become fertile ground to deepen our connection and refine our commitments. Simply stated, putting the effort into knowing ourselves can only help us know others better. Loving ourselves is essential if we want to live a good life. 🙏🏽🌎 #yungpueblo
